00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:08.900
So today is a specific way
to solve linear differential

00:00:08.900 --> 00:00:09.690
equations.

00:00:09.690 --> 00:00:12.970
I'll take second order
equations as a good example.

00:00:12.970 --> 00:00:16.600
This way is called
variation of parameters,

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:22.970
and it will lead us to a formula
for the answer, an integral.

00:00:22.970 --> 00:00:26.730
So that's the big step, to get
from the differential equation

00:00:26.730 --> 00:00:30.070
to y of t equal a
certain integral.

00:00:30.070 --> 00:00:32.310
That integral will
involve the right hand

00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:34.440
side, of course, the source.

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:37.320
And if we can do
the integration,

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:39.900
then we get a complete answer.

00:00:39.900 --> 00:00:43.900
But in any case, we get a
nice form for the answer.

00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:45.130
OK.

00:00:45.130 --> 00:00:47.850
So what's the idea?

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:51.260
So we're looking for
a particular solution.

00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:53.810
Today is about a
particular solution.

00:00:53.810 --> 00:00:59.140
We have to know two null
solutions to get started.

00:00:59.140 --> 00:01:04.319
So we must know these, y1
and y2, null solutions,

00:01:04.319 --> 00:01:06.690
with f equals 0.

00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:09.870
And of course we do
know two null solutions

00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:14.850
when those coefficients
b and c are constants.

00:01:14.850 --> 00:01:19.050
And we'll do it as a good
example, the most important

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:20.570
example.

00:01:20.570 --> 00:01:24.170
But maybe sometimes we can
find the null solutions

00:01:24.170 --> 00:01:28.890
when B and t are changing
in time, time varying,

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:31.740
and that's all to the good.

00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:34.500
Those problems are
not easy to solve.

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.340
But it's really
constant coefficients

00:01:37.340 --> 00:01:39.250
that we know it works.

00:01:39.250 --> 00:01:39.750
OK.

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:41.620
What's the idea?

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:48.430
So the idea is to use y1
and y2, the null solutions.

00:01:48.430 --> 00:01:53.570
If we multiply by constants,
we get another null solution

00:01:53.570 --> 00:01:55.230
by linearity.

00:01:55.230 --> 00:02:00.380
But the idea is to
multiply them by functions.

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:03.610
The varying, those
constants are not constant,

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.120
they are varying parameters.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:09.600
So this would be the
form of the solution.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:14.820
And we want to find a c1
and a c2 depending on t,

00:02:14.820 --> 00:02:19.500
so that the differential
equation above it is solved.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.560
So of course, I'm going to
plug that into the differential

00:02:22.560 --> 00:02:27.550
equation and find out the
conditions on c1 and c2.

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:33.450
May I just jump to the result?

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:36.090
This will satisfy that equation.

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:41.920
We know that y1
and y2 satisfy it

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:44.660
with a 0 on the right-hand side.

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:48.500
So we just have to--
So it's c1 of t and c2

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:53.510
of t that are going
to deal with the f.

00:02:53.510 --> 00:02:59.400
So here is the result
after putting it in there.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:06.600
I discover that c1 prime,
the derivative of t,

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:16.900
comes into it times y1 plus
c2 prime times y2 equaling 0

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:21.550
will give me one equation
for c1 prime and c2 prime.

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:25.570
The other equation
for c1 prime times--

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:34.290
We'll multiply y1 prime
plus c2 prime y2 prime.

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:37.020
Of course, prime
means the derivative.

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.250
And that, when I'm plugging
all this into the equation,

00:03:41.250 --> 00:03:44.620
I'm going to see an f of
t on the right-hand side.

00:03:44.620 --> 00:03:49.050
I have two equations
at each time.

00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:54.540
At each time instant I have
two ordinary linear equations.

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:59.110
They're straight lines
in the c1, c2 plane.

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:00.050
They intersect.

00:04:00.050 --> 00:04:03.040
We know how to solve--
The most basic problem

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:07.140
of linear algebra, solve two
equations and two unknowns.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:10.140
And we do that for each
t, and we get an answer.

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:16.589
So this leads us to c1 and
c2 and they depend on t.

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:22.740
Because-- Well,
actually it leads us

00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:26.050
